AB  - Introduction: Studies of childbearing adolescents document a "protective" effect of pregnancy on trajectories of alcohol and other substance use, although it is unclear how patterns differ when pregnancies result in miscarriage or abortion. Previous studies have relied on between-person designs with limited ability to account for pre-existing group differences. The present study investigated the association between childbirth, miscarriage, and abortion on within-individual changes in adolescent alcohol, marijuana, and cigarette use from pre-conception to post-pregnancy. To examine directionality of effects, we additionally tested the reverse path: whether changes in substance use precede pregnancy outcomes. Method(s): Participants included 2,184 girls (52% Black) oversampled from low-income neighborhoods. Alcohol, cigarette, and marijuana use and pregnancy outcomes were self-reported annually fromage 11-20. Fixed-effects models examined substance use change during the year of each pregnancy outcome relative to pre-childbirth/miscarriage/abortion levels and tested whether changes were sustained in subsequent years. Secondary analyses tested substance use predicting likelihood of pregnancy outcomes. By design, fixed-effects models controlled for all potential time-stable confounds (Allison, 2009); we included age, depression, and peer substance use as time-varying covariates. Result(s): Significant within-person reductions in alcohol (IRR = 0.75, p < 0.01), marijuana (IRR = 0.71, p < 0.01), and cigarette use (IRR = 0.83, p < 0.01) occurred during the year of first births relative to pre-pregnancy levels, and reductions were maintained after birth. No changes emerged during year of miscarriage, although alcohol (IRR = 0.69, p < 0.01) and cigarette use (IRR = 0.85, p = 0.02) decreased after miscarriage. Abortion was not associated with changes in alcohol relative to pre-pregnancy levels (p's>0.05); however, marijuana (IRR = 1.22, p = 0.04) and cigarette use (IRR = 1.34, p = 0.01) significantly increased during year of abortion, with cigarette increasesmaintained after year of abortion. No evidence supported reverse causation (p's >0.05). Conclusion(s): Findings highlight important differences in substance use patterns based on pregnancy outcome. Results are consistent with the protective effects of childbirth on alcohol and other substance use, whereas alcohol use during the year of miscarriage and abortion did not differ from pre-pregnancy levels. The year of abortion may be a critical period of increased cigarette and marijuana use, although research is needed to elucidate underlying mechanisms. Substance use screening and intervention among pregnant teens is essential, given continuing alcohol,marijuana, and cigarette use after certain pregnancy outcomes.
