AB  - Previous research found that women who terminated unwanted pregnancies had higher levels of binge drinking subsequent to termination seeking than those who carried unwanted pregnancies to term. Women who terminated maintained levels of binge drinking after termination, whereas women who gave birth reduced binge drinking and maintained some of this reduction over two and a half years. Neither group surpassed their pre-pregnancy level of binge drinking. This study examines possible moderators of the relationship between terminating an unwanted pregnancy and subsequent binge drinking over 2.5 years. Data are from the Turnaway Study, a prospective, longitudinal study of U.S. women seeking pregnancy termination. Participants presented just before a facility's gestational limit and received terminations (Near Limits, n = 452) or just beyond the limit and were denied terminations (Turnaways, n = 231). Analyses were conducted with mixed effects logistic regression with three way interactions between baseline characteristics, study group, and time. The relationship between termination and subsequent binge drinking was not modified by age, child sex abuse, recent physical violence, history of depression/anxiety, drug use prior to pregnancy recognition, or difficulty deciding to terminate. Parity did modify the relationship between termination and subsequent binge drinking. Among parous women (i.e., women with previous live births), the relationship looked similar to the relationship in previous research. Among nulliparous women, however, the relationship differed, with the reduction in binge drinking among Turnaways less sustained over time and binge drinking among nulliparous Near Limits and Turnaways converging by 2.5 years. While having a baby compared to terminating a pregnancy was associated with a sustained reduction in binge drinking over 2.5 years for parous women, this pattern differed for women who were nulliparous at the time they sought to terminate the pregnancy. Contrary to the hypothesis that the transition to parenting changes subsequent drinking, we found that the transition to parenting for women whose first birth is from an unwanted pregnancy is not associated with a sustained reduction in binge drinking. This suggests that previous research that has found sustained reductions in binge drinking during the transition to parenting may not apply to women who did not want to continue the pregnancy.
