The study was based on three hypotheses about the nature of the desire to have a child in relation to parental ties. The first was based on the idea that psychosexual and emotional maturity was greater in young mothers than in those who decided to have an abortion. The second hypothesis considered that this relative psychoaffective and psychosexual immaturity could be based on great parental permissiveness, while a stricter upbringing in young mothers would have favoured the establishment of the identification ties necessary to complete a pregnancy. The third hypothesis predicted a personality structure and functioning in psychometric tests within normal limits for both groups, but also a more efficient capacity for symbolisation in young mothers than in those who had had an abortion. Abortion would therefore be the equivalent of “acting out” related to the lack of capacity for symbolisation.

The contrast of these hypotheses was based on an experimental and statistical methodology rigorously applied to the two samples. The psychometric tests administered to each subject allowed the clinical verification of each of the stated hypotheses. In order to obtain statistical values, the clinical data were analyzed using non-parametric tests valid for two equal samples.

Although both groups were clinically normal, the degree of psycho-affective and psychosexual maturity was greater in the young mothers than in the other group. The cause of this affective “immaturity” could be linked to failures in the process of individuation-separation due to a partial fixation in the mirror stage (Lacan) which would block the access of young women with abortions to the depressive position (Klein), while such access would be easier for young mothers.

It was also observed that this partial fixation in the mirror stage in young women with abortions could depend on a lack of parental symbolic representations (especially paternal), which would facilitate identification with an archaic and all-powerful mother, within a family model that is too permissive. On the contrary, in young mothers, the achievement of an identification with a differentiated mother would be based on more stable parental symbolic representations, consistent with a more structuring family organization.

In this way, fixation on the mirror stage would turn abortion into the equivalent of “acting out,” due to the failure of the symbolic internalization of a differentiated mother, blocking access to the depressive position.

In the light of these clinical findings, the fixation on the mirror stage seems to require work that favours the subject's maturation, in order to prevent the repetition of successive abortions and the risk of the woman slipping into psychopathological territory. In the same clinical framework, this work opens new avenues for the study of some conditions related to the desire to give birth, such as infertility, post-partum depression and even infanticide, insofar as they are phenomena that deviate from psychological normality."; 
