AB  - Prior research into the effects of substance use during pregnancy on pregnancy outcomes has relied heavily on cross-sectional studies. Cross-sectional studies are vulnerable to social desirability and recall biases so these studies may yield misleading results. The objective of this project was to examine the effects of tobacco, alcohol, and illicit drugs on pregnancy outcomes for women in a national longitudinal survey that was less vulnerable to bias.    The National Youth Survey, a longitudinal national probability survey that followed 1,725 subjects who were 11 to 17 years old at the initial assessment, was used to determine pregnancy outcomes including elective abortion, problem pregnancy and miscarriage. These outcomes were examined among female subjects (N = 807) across six assessment periods over an eight-year time period using generalized logit models.    These models showed that subjects who used alcohol, cocaine, or amphetamines were significantly more likely to seek elective abortions than non-users. Weekly alcohol users and daily tobacco users also experienced significantly more problem pregnancies than non-users. Victimization was shown to be associated with decreased normal pregnancies. Higher SES was associated with fewer elective abortions. When tobacco and alcohol use were controlled for, the relationships remained significant for marijuana, cocaine, and amphetamines suggesting use of alcohol and tobacco predicted negative outcomes better than use of illicit substances.
