AB  - Seriously disturbed women, faced with unwanted, unintended, or unfeasible pregnancies, frequently consider the choice of abortion or relinquishment. No studies contrasting abortion and relinquishment within the psychiatric population are available as an aid to decision making. The present study, therefore, was undertaken.    Female patients with major psychiatric disorders were recruited and interviewed (using an originally designed instrument). Participants formed three groups: Abortion $(n = 36),$ Relinquishment $(n = 38),$ and Both Occurrences $(n = 45).$ They had mixed ethnicities, low socioeconomic status, an average age 40, and eleven years since their last reproductive loss. Groups were equivalent on psychiatric diagnoses and demographic variables.    It was hypothesized that the experience of relinquishment relative to abortion would be followed by more distressing emotional responses and disturbing psychosocial consequences. Opinions on reproductive losses and psychosocial characteristics were expected to differ among the three groups. Finally, it was predicted that interrelationships would be found between: (a) opinions on reproductive losses, (b) satisfaction with the decision/experience, and (c) responses to loss.    Significant results of the statistical analyses lent support to all hypotheses. With respect to relinquishment as opposed to abortion experiences: (a) more participants reported immediate symptoms and present psychiatric disturbances related to losses, (b) higher negative scores on scales of immediate symptoms, current disturbances, and emotions were reported. The findings contradicted past research in that participants coped better with abortion than previously asserted and suggested that patients considering relinquishment should be informed of the traumatic sequelae.    Participants with both kinds of reproductive losses had significantly higher rates of physical and sexual abuse, rape, and past substance abuse. Thus, they may need special attention and evaluation for post-traumatic stress disorder. Significant correlational findings suggest that the study variables have predictive value and may be useful in helping a woman when she is considering terminating a pregnancy by abortion or giving up the custody of a child. Health care costs are discussed and increased family planning services is suggested as well as obtaining reproductive histories on a routine basis. The findings imply that reproductive losses have not been adequately addressed for these patients and more research in this area is needed to better understand and help them.
