nd Exercise/Yoga. Conclusion(s): Pregnant women experience depression more in their second and third trimester with leading factors of physical violence and lack of partner support while anxiety hit them in their first and second trimester more ofently. The most common risk factors were previous bad obstetrical history and lack of spouse support. Screening methods and establishment of counselling sessions for anxiety and depression should be incorporated in existing antenatal programs for detection and treatment of early symptoms of these psychiatric issues.
